SIMPLE: stereotype
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Stereotype
<hw>Ste"re*o*type</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>
<ety>[<ets>Stereo-</ets> + <ets>-type</ets>: cf. F.
<ets>st⟦eacute⟧r⟦eacute⟧otype</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A plate
forming an exact facsimile of a page of type or of an engraving, used in
printing books, etc.; specifically, a plate with type-metal face, used
for printing.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ A <xex>stereotype</xex>, or <xex>stereotypr plate</xex>,
is made by setting movable type as for ordinary printing; from these a
cast is taken in plaster of Paris, paper pulp, or the like, and upon
this cast melted type metal is poured, which, when hardened, makes a
solid page or column, from which the impression is taken as from
type.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The art or process of making such plates, or of
executing work by means of them.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Stereotype block</b></col>, <cd>a block, usually of wood,
to which a stereotype plate is attached while being used in
printing.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Stereotype</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Stereotype
<hw>Ste"re*o*type</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Stereotyped</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Stereotyping</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <ety>[Cf.
F. <ets>st⟦eacute⟧r⟦eacute⟧otyper</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To
prepare for printing in stereotype; to make the stereotype plates of;
<as>as, to <ex>stereotype</ex> the Bible</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Fig.: To make firm or permanent; to fix.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Powerful causes tending to <qex>stereotype</qex> and aggravate the
poverty of old conditions.</q> <rj><qau>Duke of Argyll
(1887).</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Stereotyped</ent>⟦br⟧
